pnp:ClientSidePage.Title: Finance team recognised for adoption of OCR scanning technology for invoices

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
“Work smarter” is the motto of the Finance team who recently recieved Reward and Recognition awards for their successful implementation of an innovative invoice scanning system. The Project receives approximately 700 invoices on a normal week and 1000 invoices in the week before the end of month.  


To efficiently work through this large volume of invoices Ali Mearns, Jodie Di Girolamo and Mey Ngan employed Optical Character Recognition (OCR) software that scans invoices and automatically populates their data, without manual input. 


Finance and Admin Manager Rosina Ward drove the initiative after successfully campaigning the John Holland IT Department to trial the innovative software. The implementation of this system was a first for John Holland and the project will continue to provide feedback on its operation.

  

The persistence of Ali, Jodie and Mey proved the software a success, saving significant time, while generating a faster turn-around on invoices. 


The benefits of the OCR scanning software also reach beyond the Finance team, with suppliers and subcontractors now receiving invoice payments sooner than previously. 


Congratulations Ali, Jodie and Mey on your awards and for living the Project Value 'Innovate'.

pnp:ClientSidePage.Title: Controlling Critical Risks – Emergency Response Training conducted 40 meters high in the sky

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
With safety front of mind, the JHCPB tower crane crew recently harnessed up and took turns lowering from the tower crane's 40-meter high platform in a recent course of Emergency Control Training. 


Accompanied by the ventilation building crew, the tower crane team learned the essential intricacies of vertical rescue training and working at heights with training provider Skyhooks. 


Consisting of more than harnesses and pulleys, the team gained technical skills including setting up and inspecting the rescue kit, and learning what to do in the case of an emergency. 


The training supplemented a two-day tower crane rescue course that was conducted atop a storage container at the Training Academy in Homebush. 


The tower crane and ventilation building crews will undergo bi-annual 'refresher' training.

pnp:ClientSidePage.Title: Deliver - First Girder installed in CWL Pigtail Bridge

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
The first girder for the Pigtail Bridge was installed last week in a successful three hour operation overseen by the CWL and Safety teams. 


The 57.9tonne girder is made from Australian steel and was fabricated by Haywards in Tasmania before being transported to the CWL site. 


Sizing a significant 24 meters long and 2.8m wide with bolted steel outriggers, this large section of bridging was installed atop a temporary pier and a permanent pier that sits adjacent to the existing Inner West Light Rail line. 


This precarious location made the installation plans especially complex, as the Pigtail Bridge site also neighbors residents in Annandale. 


With the impact of nightworks on residents in mind, Mitch Vaughan negotiated a daytime installation for the girder with Transdev, having proven that the planned Drop'N'Go technique was safe and efficient. 


And efficient it was. Completing two hours sooner than expected, the complex restraint and support system facilitated the girder's smooth landing with zero issues. 


This success was due to the detailed planning and collaboration between the design engineers, CWL team, Traffic team, cranage subcontractor Borgers and Transdev. 


Roger Posgate and the Community and Environment teams also played an integral role in the girder's success, working with local council, the EPA and transport subcontractors to facilitate the girder's smooth delivery to site. 


Now the girder is installed, the CWL team have promptly begun building another temporary pier support and permanent pier in anticipation of two girders that are due for installation in March.

pnp:ClientSidePage.Title: Daytime Testing of Light Rail Vehicles (LRVs)Underway

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Daytime testing is an exciting milestone with many opportunities to see LRVs moving up and down the light rail system! At the same time, it is important for everyone in the community to be mindful of electronic traffic signage, the presence of traffic management personnel and moving LRVs at intersections and crossings.


Information you need to know:

  • Daytime testing of the LRVs is currently focused between Gungahlin Place and Nullarbor Avenue. In the coming weeks the testing area will be expanded to include the track from Mitchell to Gungahlin Place.
  • Testing activities will continue Monday to Friday, at night, as well as during the day in three shifts 5:00am to 1:00pm, 1:00pm to 9:00pm and 9:00pm to 5:00am.
  • A minimum of two (2) LRVs will be on the tracks testing during the day.
  • T traffic lights will regulate LRV movements at intersections. During testing, these will be operational, controlling traffic movements along Flemington Road intersections with Hinder Street, Kate Crace Street and Manning Clark Crescent.

T Traffic Lights

T trafﬁc lights are for light rail vehicles only. If you see a red ‘T’ you don’t have to stop, this is instructing the LRV to stop. A white ‘T’ is instructing the LRV to go. If you see a white ‘T’ don’t try to cross the intersection,  wait for the green arrow. Remember, the road rules have not changed. If we all follow the rules, we all stay safe.

 

 

 

Stay Alert Around Light Rail Vehicles

Light Rail Vehicles (LRVs) are quiet and may not be heard against everyday traffic noise. Pedestrians need to stay alert around the light rail corridor and not be distracted by mobile phones or headphones. LRV drivers will sound a bell if they see pedestrians putting themselves in danger so listen out for the ‘ding-ding’. It is important to always cross at designated pedestrian crossings or intersections, and look both ways before crossing the road and light rail tracks. Take a look at and share the light rail safety resources available. 

Learn more: 

Watch out, the trams have now begun rolling down the track in daytime - The Canberra Times, 22/08/2018

Following a well deserved break for our teams, tunnelling is now well underway across our project with TBM 4 (Alice) recently relaunched towards the CBD.

Alice joins TBM 3 (Millie), who has since progressed more than 400m towards the Town Hall Station after being relaunched in December.

Catch the TBM reassembly and TBM 3 relaunch prior to Christmas on our latest Domain timelapse video. 

In the CBD, the transfer of TBM 1 (Joan) via the platform rail tunnels at the State Library site continues. This followed the completion of the 1km section of Metro Tunnel between Parkville and the CBD prior to Christmas.

In coming weeks, TBM 1 will be recommissioned and relaunched towards Town Hall Station on the last leg of its journey.

TBM 2 (Meg), carving a parallel 1km route from Parkville, is expected to breakthrough at the State Library site in the coming weeks.

Tunnelling will be completed on the Metro Tunnel Project later this year.

pnp:ClientSidePage.Title: November Reward and Recognition recipients announced

pnp:CanvasControlProperty.Value:
Congratulations to our 17 CYP Reward and Recognition Program recipients for November!

We received a total of 73 nominations across the project for the month with a number of our successful recipients nominated multiple times, which is fantastic! 

It's great to see so many of our employees demonstrating our project values of Successful teams, Empowerment, Accountability and Results Orientated.

Plaques and $100 gift cards will be given to all our successful recipients (listed below) at team briefings/toolboxes in the coming days.   

As we have two shorter work months ahead of us, we will be combining December and January nominations and the due date is Monday 25 January 2021.

All nominations can be completed online through the online nomination form located on the intranet or a hard copy which are located at all sites.

Thanks again to all nominees for your excellent work and to those who are completing the nomination forms.  Keep up the amazing work and we look forward to receiving and reading many more.

Our Project achieved another major milestone with the successful breakthrough of TBM 2 into State Library Station on 11 February.

This is the 8th TBM breakthrough for our Project. 

TBM 2 has tunnelled one kilometre from Parkville Station, and will now be transferred through the State Library Station site before relaunch to complete the final section between State Library Station and Town Hall.

Earlier this week, TBM 1 relaunched from State Library Station to commence tunnelling towards Town Hall Station. 

In the East, TBM 3 and 4 are making excellent progress on their journey towards to the CBD. TBM 3 has now reached the halfway mark to the CBD with 900 metres of tunnel completed, and TBM 4 has completed 230 metres. 

Congratulations to our tunnelling team, and to our CBD team for ensuring that the cavern was ready for the arrival of the TBM.

Hi team,

This month kicks off some significant milestones for the project including our busy 2021 program of occupations in the east and west to progress and the completion of our first separable portions at the eastern and western portals.


There are more weekends on than off between now and Easter, and I hope that everyone was able to get some good rest over the Christmas break and early January.


As we head towards the final stages of handover of the eastern portal to CYP, complete works in the western portal decline structure, and finalise preparations for our upcoming occupations in the west and east, I would like to acknowledge the tremendous work of everyone on RIA, that has gone into satisfying the requirements from both RPV and MTM (and V/Line who we sometimes forget to mention). The collective effort of everyone at RIA has paved the way for this complex handover process to take place. Feedback from our key stakeholders have been very positive to date.


The wider Melbourne metropolitan and regional rail network has undergone some significant changes this month, including the introduction of a new timetable. The new timetable means passengers can move in and around the networks on 280 new metropolitan services each week, more room on trains and platforms and have more options to plan travel as we move towards COVID normal. With this new timetable in place, the first step in preparing for the Metro Tunnel, its bigger trains and more services has started. It is exciting to acknowledge the wider picture and to know that we have all had a hand in making this happen.

Following today’s announcement by the Victorian government, as RIA is deemed State Critical Infrastructure, work will continue at our project sites and offices as it previously did during Stage 4 Restrictions.


A ‘confirmation of travel’ letter has been issued to all staff this afternoon, which you can print and carry with you if you need to attend our workplace or cannot work from home.


To help minimise the movement of people throughout the community – everyone is encouraged to work from home if you can during this time.


Face masks are now mandatory at all times when leaving your home and this applies to both indoor and outdoor settings. Please ensure you use the QR Code check-in system and wear a face mask at all times when attending our offices / sites.


I would like to thank all team members involved in continuing the hard work we have put in, and remind you to stay safe and look after each other. We appreciate the hard work that is going into preparing for and executing our 2021 program of works.


Regards,

Matt Durham

ARTO Interface and Access Manager

The Rozelle Interchange and Iron Cove Link will provide a new underground motorway interchange to City West Link and provide an underground bypass of Victoria Road between Iron Cove Bridge and Anzac Bridge, with links to the future Western Harbour Tunnel.


The interchange in Rozelle will be mostly underground and located at the site of the old Rozelle Rail Yards. By building the interchange mostly underground, the project will deliver new active transport options in Rozelle and up to 10 hectares of new open space.

Site Help


For this site to be a reliable source of truth for our project, some aspects of it are controlled by the Project Workbench Site Owner.


If you have ideas for the site or have any questions about it, please contact the Project Workbench Site Owner - for example:

  • Help with this Project Workbench Site
  • Creation of a new lists
  • Creation of new content, including news, alert, pages
  • Creation of new Document Libraries


Training


Whilst the Project Workbench Site has been designed to be as intuitive as possible, first time users of the site might like some training in order to make the most of it, especially to understand why certain things need to be done in a certain way.


For more training information, please contact the Project Workbench Site Owner.
